      <hedline>
        <hl1>Schools and Parents</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wendy Dembeck letter comments on August 16 article on success of KIPP Academy</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Seeking to Clone Schools of Success for Poor'' (front page, Aug. 16): As a teacher beginning her 31st year in the classroom in September, I can vouch for the factors that make the KIPP program a success: discipline, challenging work, reinforcement and parental involvement.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Seeking to Clone Schools of Success for Poor'' (front page, Aug. 16): As a teacher beginning her 31st year in the classroom in September, I can vouch for the factors that make the KIPP program a success: discipline, challenging work, reinforcement and parental involvement.</p>
        <p>These elements provide focus for young minds and help set goals. Unfortunately, this approach does not address many of the social ills plaguing some of today's children, particularly inattentive parents who will not or cannot ''sign contracts.'' What happens to those children?</p>
        <p>WENDY DEMBECK  Warwick, N.Y., Aug. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
